The paper studies a rumor spreading protocol on complete graphs, which involves the use of randomness and has implications for the efficiency of the protocol. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories. 

cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is a likely category because the paper analyzes the time complexity of the rumor spreading protocol and considers the impact of reducing the amount of randomness used. 

cs.NE (Networks and Internet Architecture) is also a likely category because the paper studies a protocol for spreading information in a network, and analyzes the efficiency of the protocol in terms of the number of rounds needed to inform all nodes. 

cs.IT (Information Theory) is a possible category because the paper considers the tradeoff between time and randomness in the rumor spreading protocol, which could be viewed as an information-theoretic problem. 

cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is another possible category because the paper studies a protocol for spreading information in a network, which is a key topic in the study of social and information networks. 

cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) is a less likely category, but still possible, because the paper considers the efficiency of a protocol for spreading information in a network, which could be viewed as a game between the nodes in the network.
